---
title: Sugar and Spice Pork Chops with Roasted Carrots, Parsnips, and Red Onion
description: If you think pork chops are dull, think again. In this recipe, the tender cut takes on a shine, literally. You’ll be coating them in a glistening glaze that marries caramelized sugar with herb-y thyme and a hint of cayenne heat. On the side, we’ve got roasted carrots, onions, and parsnips—yep, parsnips (trust us, you’ll love ’em for their natural sweetness).
image: https://img.hellofresh.com/f_auto,fl_lossy,h_640,q_auto,w_1200/hellofresh_s3/image/sugar-and-spice-pork-chops-cb79427e.jpg
pdf: https://www.hellofresh.com/recipecards/card/sugar-and-spice-pork-chops-5a0dda1d450cfa2ca127cd64-1fdf80e1.pdf
servings: 2
source: https://www.hellofresh.com/recipes/sugar-and-spice-pork-chops-5a0dda1d450cfa2ca127cd64
course: main course
author: HelloFresh
time required: 35 minutes
cuisine: North America
nutrition:
  calories: 550 kcal
  fat: 18 g
  saturated fat: 3.5 g
  carbohydrates: 62 g
  sugar: 25 g
  protein: 41 g
  fiber: 15 g
  sodium: 450 mg
---

Wash and dry all produce. Adjust rack to middle position and preheat oven to 400
degrees. Peel @carrots{2%unit} and @parsnip{2%unit}. Slice both into ¼-inch-thick
rounds on a slight diagonal. Halve and peel @red onion{1%unit}, then cut into
½-inch wedges. Strip leaves from @thyme{¼%ounce} and discard stems; roughly
chop leaves. Mince or grate @garlic{2%clove}.

Toss together carrots, parsnips, onion, half the thyme, @olive oil{1%tablespoon},
and a pinch of @salt{pinch} and @pepper{pinch} on a #baking sheet{}. Roast in
oven until tender and lightly browned, ~{23-25%minutes}, tossing halfway
through.

Heat a drizzle of @vegetable oil{2%teaspoon} in a large pan over medium-high
heat. Pat @pork chops{12%ounce} dry with a #paper towel{}. Season all over with
salt and pepper. Add to pan and cook until browned and nearly cooked through,
~{3-4%minutes} per side. Remove from pan and set aside.

Heat a drizzle of oil in same pan over medium heat. Add garlic and toss until
fragrant, about ~{30%seconds}. Stir in a pinch of @cayenne pepper{1%teaspoon}
(to taste—it's spicy), @sugar{1%tablespoon}, remaining thyme,
@chicken stock concentrate{1%unit}, and ½ cup water, scraping up any browned
bits on bottom. Bring to a simmer and let bubble until reduced by half,
~{2-3%minutes}. Season with salt and pepper.

Return pork to pan and turn to coat in glaze. Cook until pork reaches desired
doneness, ~{1-2%minutes} longer. Using #tongs{}, pick up each piece and gently
shake above pan to let excess glaze drip off, then transfer to a #cutting board{}.

Thinly slice pork. Divide veggies and pork between plates, then drizzle with any
remaining glaze.

> If you think pork chops are dull, think again. The tender cut takes on a shine,
> literally, coating them in a glistening glaze that marries caramelized sugar
> with herb-y thyme and a hint of cayenne heat. Parboiling parsnips is necessary to
> get them tender and naturally sweet.